Son quienes tienen mayores posibilidades de ser perjudicados


912
00:37:27,100 --> 00:37:29,140
y cuyas voces necesitan más ser escuchadas.


913
00:37:29,140 --> 00:37:30,740
Son quienes más necesitan ayuda.


914
00:37:31,780 --> 00:37:34,780
Estos últimos años, nuestro consumo de carbón ha sido extremadamente alto.


915
00:37:34,780 --> 00:37:36,580
Como resultado, la calidad del carbón que usamos ha disminuido.


916
00:37:36,580 --> 00:37:38,060
Además no lavamos nuestro carbón


917
00:37:38,060 --> 00:37:39,660
y casi no hay controles sobre las emisiones.


918
00:37:39,660 --> 00:37:41,140
Este es el resultado.


919
00:37:42,020 --> 00:37:42,780
Los lugares de China


920
00:37:42,780 --> 00:37:44,860
con mayor consumo de carbón


921
00:37:44,860 --> 00:37:48,060
también tienen las mayores concentraciones de PM 2.5.


922
00:37:48,100 --> 00:37:50,380
La forma más fácil de limpiar nuestro ambiente


923
00:37:50,380 --> 00:37:52,660
sería reducir nuestro consumo de carbón a menos de 2 mil millones de toneladas.


924
00:37:52,660 --> 00:37:54,220
Ello garantizaría cielos azules.


925
00:37:54,220 --> 00:37:55,540
Si no podemos alcanzar dicha meta,


926
00:37:55,540 --> 00:37:57,540
podemos tratar de centralizar la quema de carbón


927
00:37:57,540 --> 00:37:59,660
y reemplazar la de “carbón chatarra” con el empleo de centrales eléctricas de carbón.


928
00:37:59,660 --> 00:38:01,300
Como siguiente paso,


929
00:38:01,300 --> 00:38:02,620
si aún no podemos lograr mejorar el ambiente,


930
00:38:02,620 --> 00:38:05,020
podemos intentar lavar el “carbón chatarra” que usamos.


931
00:38:05,020 --> 00:38:07,700
Si se lava todo el “carbón chatarra”, ¿cuál sería el efecto sobre las emisiones?


932
00:38:07,700 --> 00:38:09,140
Como mínimo reduciría nuestras emisiones a la mitad.
933
00:38:09,140 --> 00:38:10,980
Actualmente, podemos realizar dos cambios


934
00:38:10,980 --> 00:38:13,060
Primero, debemos reducir el consumo de carbón


935
00:38:13,060 --> 00:38:14,220
o podemos lavar nuestro carbón.


936
00:38:14,220 --> 00:38:15,960
El Artículo 23° de la Ley de Protección de la Atmósfera


937
00:38:15,960 --> 00:38:16,980
señala que el gobierno promueve el lavado y la mejora en la calidad del carbón,


938
00:38:16,980 --> 00:38:18,300
la reducción del contenido de polvo y azufre en el carbón ,


939
00:38:18,300 --> 00:38:19,540
y restricciones en las extracción de carbón con alto contenido de polvo y azufre.


940
00:38:19,540 --> 00:38:21,120
“1° de los Diez artículos sobre protección de la atmósfera”:


941
00:38:21,120 --> 00:38:22,210
Deben renovarse los pequeños incineradores de carbón,


942
00:38:22,210 -->  :38:23,870
acelerando la des-sulfurización y la reducción de componentes de nitrógeno y polvo.   


943
00:38:23,870 --> 00:38:28,580
En 2014, el PM se redujo 11.1% de su nivel máximo en 74 ciudades,


944
00:38:28,930 --> 00:38:31,980
pero sólo 8 ciudades alcanzaron los estándares fijados por el gobierno.


945
00:38:31,980 --> 00:38:34,180
Si pudiésemos implementar eficazmente todas las medidas de protección ambiental vigentes,


946
00:38:34,180 --> 00:38:36,700
sólo las que tenemos actualmente, y hacerlas cumplir al 100%,


947
00:38:36,700 --> 00:38:39,700
nuestras emisiones de polvo y dióxido de azufre


948
00:38:39,700 --> 00:38:41,060
disminuirían en un 60% respecto a su nivel actual,


949
00:38:41,060 --> 00:38:43,420
nuestras emisiones de óxido de nitrógeno serían un 35% más bajas.




950
00:38:43,420 --> 00:38:45,580
Para solucionar el problema ambiental en China,


951
00:38:45,580 --> 00:38:47,300
primero, necesitamos tener una mejor gestión,


952
00:38:47,300 --> 00:38:49,300
segundo, necesitamos una gestión todavía mejor,


953
00:38:49,300 --> 00:38:51,420
tercero, necesitamos una aún mejor gestión.


954
00:38:51,420 --> 00:38:52,580
El presidente Xi Jinping dijo:


955
00:38:52,580 --> 00:38:55,700
“La dignidad de las leyes depende de su cumplimiento”.


956
00:38:56,260 --> 00:38:57,380
China necesitó 30 años


957
00:38:57,380 --> 00:38:59,060
para completar un proceso de industrialización


958
00:38:59,060 --> 00:39:00,260
que tomó cien años en otros países.


959
00:39:00,260 --> 00:39:02,340
Por tanto, por encima de la polución producida por el carbón,


960
00:39:02,340 --> 00:39:03,980
tenemos que además hacer frente


961
00:39:03,980 --> 00:39:05,060
a la polución generada por el petróleo.


962
00:39:05,060 --> 00:39:07,100
¿Así que qué pasa con nuestro petróleo?


963
00:39:07,100 --> 00:39:08,860
La mayoría es quemado por automóviles.


964
00:39:08,860 --> 00:39:11,220
En diez años, el número de automóviles en China


965
00:39:11,220 --> 00:39:12,540
ha aumentado aproximadamente en 100 millones.


966
00:39:12,540 --> 00:39:14,900
Fijándonos específicamente en Beijing en el 2010,


967
00:39:14,900 --> 00:39:17,060
¿cuántos automóviles se añadieron sólo ese año?


968
00:39:17,060 --> 00:39:18,020
800.000 más.


969
00:39:18,020 --> 00:39:19,060
¿Qué significan 800000 automóviles más?


970
00:39:19,060 --> 00:39:23,580
Si todos esos vehículos fuesen colocados en fila de un extremo a otro, se extenderían de Beijing a Shenzen.


971
00:39:23,580 --> 00:39:24,660
y de vuelta a Beijing.


972
00:39:24,660 --> 00:39:27,180
Ese ha sido el incremento de un año.


973
00:39:27,180 --> 00:39:28,940
El resultado es el siguiente:


974
00:39:28,940 --> 00:39:31,340
la principal fuente de PM2.5 dentro de Beijing


975
00:39:31,340 --> 00:39:34,260
son esos vehículos. 


976
00:39:34,260 --> 00:39:35,940
Pero hay otra ciudad que me sorprendió.


977
00:39:35,940 --> 00:39:39,660
Esta ciudad está bajo la niebla más de 200 días al año.


978
00:39:41,340 --> 00:39:43,340
Pueden adivinar qué ciudad es,


979
00:39:46,020 --> 00:39:47,340
¿cuál de ésta?


980
00:39:50,620 --> 00:39:52,540
Miremos otra foto


981
¿Qinghai dicen?


982
00:39:54,100 --> 00:39:56,780
¿Qingdao?


983
00:39:56,780 --> 00:39:59,180
Hangzhou



984
00:39:59,180 --> 00:40:00,660
Honestamente, estoy tan concertada como ustedes.


985
00:40:00,660 --> 00:40:02,380
Porque siempre pensé


986
00:40:02,380 --> 00:40:04,820
que este era el escenario de la lluvia brumosa descrita en tantos poemas famosos.


987
00:40:04,820 --> 00:40:06,780
Más tarde llamé a la Agencia de Protección Ambiental de Hangzhou


988
00:40:06,780 --> 00:40:07,900
y me confirmaron aquel dato.


989
00:40:07,900 --> 00:40:10,420
Ello se debe a que la tasa de propiedad de automóvil por habitante en Hangzhou


990
00:40:10,420 --> 00:40:11,100
es la más alta entre todas las ciudades de China.


991
00:40:11,100 --> 00:40:13,220
En promedio, hay un carro por cada dos habitantes.


992
00:40:13,220 --> 00:40:14,380
Así que los vehículos de Hangzhou


993
00:40:14,380 --> 00:40:16,380
contribuyen a cerca del 40% de la contaminación del aire en ella.


994
00:40:16,380 --> 00:40:19,500
Do more cars necessarily mean more pollution?


995
00:40:19,500 --> 00:40:20,740
Here’s a question we often hear


996
00:40:20,740 --> 00:40:22,420
Aren’t there more cars in Tokyo than in Beijing?


997
00:40:22,420 --> 00:40:25,460
Why don’t we see such severe pollution in Tokyo?


998
00:40:25,460 --> 00:40:28,260
This is the explanation given by the Beijing Municipal Commission of Transport:


999
00:40:28,260 --> 00:40:31,940
More than 90% of Tokyo's residents commute by rail


1000
00:40:31,940 --> 00:40:34,260
Less than 6% of them drive


1001
00:40:34,260 --> 00:40:35,900
What about in Beijing?


1002
00:40:35,900 --> 00:40:37,700
34% of Beijing residents drive cars


1003
00:40:37,700 --> 00:40:40,260
And they drive in the city center, usually stuck in traffic jams


1004
00:40:40,260 --> 00:40:41,460
When they are stuck their cars are idling


1005
00:40:41,460 --> 00:40:42,620
which doubles the rate of emissions


1006
00:40:42,620 --> 00:40:44,980
And when they brake, even more heavy metals are released


1007
00:40:44,980 --> 00:40:47,340
So every day during rush hour in Beijing


1008
00:40:47,340 --> 00:40:49,940
how much PM2.5 is emitted in one hour


1009
00:40:49,940 --> 00:40:51,580
within the 6th ring?


1010
00:40:51,580 --> 00:40:52,300
One ton


1011
00:40:53,180 --> 00:40:54,860
How many Beijing residents would choose to drive


1012
00:40:54,860 --> 00:40:56,020
if they are going somewhere within 5km?


1013
00:40:57,740 --> 00:40:59,180
Close to half


1014
00:40:59,180 --> 00:41:00,820
12% of all residents


1015
00:41:00,820 --> 00:41:03,940
would drive within 2km


1016
00:41:03,940 --> 00:41:05,460
And 7%


1017
00:41:05,460 --> 00:41:06,660
would drive within 1km


1018
00:41:06,660 --> 00:41:07,740
How far is 1km?


1019
00:41:07,740 --> 00:41:09,140
That’s a trip to the supermarket


1020
00:41:09,140 --> 00:41:10,980
or greengrocer's


1021
00:41:10,980 --> 00:41:13,380
Do we really love driving so much?


1022
00:41:13,380 --> 00:41:15,060
Perhaps a few of us do


1023
00:41:15,060 --> 00:41:17,420
But there can’t be so many irrational people, right?


1024
00:41:17,420 --> 00:41:20,580
My family owns a car, but after our child was born we made a rule


1025
00:41:20,580 --> 00:41:22,260
basically we would only drive for our parents, our kid


1026
00:41:22,260 --> 00:41:23,380
or when we go to the airport or hospital


1027
00:41:23,380 --> 00:41:26,820
When my husband goes to work every day, he rides a bicycle


1028
00:41:26,820 --> 00:41:28,260
This is how you ride a bicycle


1029
00:41:28,260 --> 00:41:29,180
in front of our apartment building


1030
00:41:30,900 --> 00:41:32,260
That’s the only way to ride


1031
00:41:32,260 --> 00:41:34,220
Why?


1032
00:41:34,220 --> 00:41:36,020
This is our bicycle lane


1033
00:41:36,020 --> 00:41:38,700
It’s almost always full of cars


1034
00:41:38,700 --> 00:41:39,820
Beijing has over 5 million vehicles


1035
00:41:39,820 --> 00:41:41,980
but only half of them have a parking space


1036
00:41:41,980 --> 00:41:43,460
But no car can park in the air


1037
00:41:43,460 --> 00:41:45,060
so you find them in bicycle lanes


1038
00:41:45,060 --> 00:41:46,540
and on sidewalks


1039
00:41:46,540 --> 00:41:48,140
That’s how they park


1040
00:41:48,140 --> 00:41:50,220
Of course, humanity is the same throughout the world


1041
00:41:50,220 --> 00:41:51,820
Without regulations, this can happen anywhere


1042
00:41:51,820 --> 00:41:53,580
Let’s check London


1043
00:41:53,580 --> 00:41:55,540
It seems they also parked like this in the old days


1044
00:41:55,540 --> 00:41:58,540
then the parking meters were installed


1045
00:41:58,540 --> 00:42:00,220
and they parked like this


1046
00:42:00,220 --> 00:42:03,260
Then London raised its parking fee and congestion charge


1047
00:42:03,260 --> 00:42:04,740
so they parked like this


1048
00:42:04,740 --> 00:42:06,380
A few days ago, I heard that people are trying the same thing in Shenzhen


1049
00:42:06,380 --> 00:42:08,900
they started to charge high parking fees


1050
00:42:08,900 --> 00:42:13,980
Then the folks in Shenzhen parked like this (laughter)


1051
00:42:13,980 --> 00:42:15,660
The same thing happened in Tokyo 50 years ago


1052
00:42:15,660 --> 00:42:16,580
It’s not that easy


1053
00:42:16,580 --> 00:42:17,860
It took them a long time


1054
00:42:17,860 --> 00:42:19,740
to clear the cars out of the way one by one


1055
00:42:19,740 --> 00:42:22,660
This is a test of meticulous city management.


1056
00:42:22,660 --> 00:42:24,860
Car-lovers have another question


1057
00:42:24,860 --> 00:42:26,820
As this photo shows


1058
00:42:26,820 --> 00:42:29,860
there are no vehicles in Beijing at midnight, are there?


1059
00:42:29,860 --> 00:42:32,260
Why is the pollution still so severe?


1060
00:42:32,260 --> 00:42:34,860
Is it really caused by cars?


1061
00:42:34,860 --> 00:42:36,260
This question also troubled me for a long time


1062
00:42:36,260 --> 00:42:38,220
Until the Chinese Academy of Sciences showed me this chart


1063
00:42:40,700 --> 00:42:42,980
Before every dawn in Beijing


1064
00:42:42,980 --> 00:42:44,660
There’s always a peak in pollution


1065
00:42:44,660 --> 00:42:46,500
It shows up consistently every day


1066
00:42:46,500 --> 00:42:48,100
At this peak, carbon emissions are about twice as high


1067
00:42:48,100 --> 00:42:50,380
as the peak in the afternoon on the same day


1068
00:42:50,380 --> 00:42:52,500
So what exactly is this?


1069
00:42:52,500 --> 00:42:53,740
I wanted to know the answer as well


1070
00:42:53,740 --> 00:42:55,060
So we went to Yanqing district of Beijing


1071
00:42:56,000 --> 00:42:58,000
Yanqing - Kangzhuang Toll Station, 2:30am 11 October 2014


1072
00:42:59,180 --> 00:43:00,140
Inspector: Halt!


1073
00:43:00,140 --> 00:43:02,140
Vehicle type: Futian Aoling


1074
00:43:02,140 --> 00:43:04,140
Displayed emissions standard: National Standard 4


1075
00:43:04,540 --> 00:43:06,460
This truck doesn't have the basic equipment for a Standard 4


1076
00:43:06,460 --> 00:43:08,140
Chai: So in fact it's not a Standard 4 vehicle


1077
00:43:08,140 --> 00:43:09,060
Driver: So what should I do?


1078
00:43:09,060 --> 00:43:10,340
Driver: I just bought this new truck


1079
00:43:10,700 --> 00:43:12,140
This is my environmental protection label


1080
00:43:12,140 --> 00:43:13,580
It was issued this year


1081
00:43:16,000 --> 00:43:17,960
Random inspection of another vehicle


1082
00:43:17,960 --> 00:43:19,100
Vehicle type: Chang'an Kaima


1083
00:43:19,100 --> 00:43:20,620
Displayed emissions standard: National Standard 3


1084
00:43:20,620 --> 00:43:22,020
What does 3.29 mean?


1085
00:43:22,020 --> 00:43:23,180
It’s above the limit


1086
00:43:23,180 --> 00:43:24,420
This is even beyond Standard 1


1087
00:43:24,420 --> 00:43:26,420
So it has no emission control device at all?


1088
00:43:26,420 --> 00:43:28,140
No, basically no emission control at all


1089
00:43:28,140 --> 00:43:28,900
He has the green label


1090
00:43:29,380 --> 00:43:30,620
It says Standard 3


1091
00:43:30,620 --> 00:43:31,260
Who issued it?


1092
00:43:31,260 --> 00:43:33,980
Hebei Province Department of Environmental Protection


1093
00:43:33,980 --> 00:43:35,420
When I bought it they said it was Standard 3


1094
00:43:35,420 --> 00:43:37,500
How could I know? I was just buying a truck


1095
00:43:37,500 --> 00:43:39,500
Finally, the car was not given an on the spot fine


1096
00:43:40,660 --> 00:43:41,940
His truck is on the green channel


1097
00:43:41,940 --> 00:43:43,500
It's carrying eggs, milk, and oil


1098
00:43:43,500 --> 00:43:44,860
It’s part of the city’s supply system


1099
00:43:44,860 --> 00:43:48,010
According to the regulations, we should not penalize this truck


1100
00:43:48,010 --> 00:43:50,300
Li Kunsheng, Director of Beijing Municipal Environmental Protection Bureau, Vehicular Emissions Department


1101
00:43:50,300 --> 00:43:51,120
Fake cars are common


1102
00:43:51,120 --> 00:43:53,700
Or if we put it in more serious terms, fake cars are everywhere


1103
00:43:53,700 --> 00:43:55,060
It's a secret kept within the automotive industry


1104
00:43:55,060 --> 00:43:56,940
90% of basic environmental protection devices are not installed


1105
00:43:56,940 --> 00:43:58,460
So how does that play out in terms of emissions?


1106
00:43:58,460 --> 00:44:00,340
If 30,000 [noncompliant] vehicles enter the city


1107
00:44:00,340 --> 00:44:02,860
It's equivalent to several million [compliant] vehicles on the road at night


1108
00:44:04,740 --> 00:44:09,380
What kind of emissions result if emission control devices are not used?


1109
00:44:09,380 --> 00:44:10,980
The quantity of particulate emissions


1110
00:44:10,980 --> 00:44:12,820
from just one vehicle [with no safeguards]


1111
00:44:12,820 --> 00:44:15,980
Is 500 times the emissions from a vehicle of National Standard 4


1112
00:44:15,980 --> 00:44:17,660
Diesel cars do not make up a big proportion of vehicles


1113
00:44:17,660 --> 00:44:18,900
It’s similar to the case of scrap coal


1114
00:44:18,900 --> 00:44:19,820
There are not many


1115
00:44:19,820 --> 00:44:21,140
Only 17% of all cars are diesel


1116
00:44:21,140 --> 00:44:23,220
but their emissions of nitrogen oxides


1117
00:44:23,220 --> 00:44:25,700
make up 70% of all vehicle emissions


1118
00:44:25,700 --> 00:44:27,420
and as for their emission of primary particles


1119
00:44:27,420 --> 00:44:28,540
relative to all vehicles?


1120
00:44:28,540 --> 00:44:30,500
99%


1121
00:44:30,500 --> 00:44:32,020
There's an even scarier aspect to this too


1122
00:44:32,020 --> 00:44:34,460
The particulates in diesel vehicle emissions


1123
00:44:34,460 --> 00:44:36,780
have exceptionally high toxicity


1124
00:44:36,780 --> 00:44:38,060
PAHs are carcinogens


1125
00:44:38,060 --> 00:44:41,660
But diesel vehicles emit PAHs on steroids


1126
00:44:41,660 --> 00:44:45,860
Nitro-PAHs, which are an order of magnitude more carcinogenic


1127
00:44:45,860 --> 00:44:47,940
When I saw those drivers of diesel vehicles in Yanqing


1128
00:44:47,940 --> 00:44:51,820
I realized that they themselves are the biggest victims of their own diesel emissions


1129
00:44:51,820 --> 00:44:54,460
They are a group at very high risk for cancer


1130
00:44:54,460 --> 00:44:57,860
Besides, it seems fairly unreasonable to punish these people


1131
00:44:57,860 --> 00:45:00,060
They spent their own money


1132
00:45:00,060 --> 00:45:01,660
They bought vehicles with legal certificates


1133
00:45:01,660 --> 00:45:02,820
issued by the government


1134
00:45:02,820 --> 00:45:04,460
What reason do we have to fine them?


1135
00:45:04,460 --> 00:45:05,860
If we want to blame someone


1136
00:45:05,860 --> 00:45:07,180
shouldn’t we start with those


1137
00:45:07,180 --> 00:45:08,900
responsible for manufacturing these fake vehicles?


1138
00:45:09,090 --> 00:45:10,670
Chai: Could you explain why


1139
00:45:10,670 --> 00:45:13,920
the emission devices weren't installed during production?


1140
00:45:13,920 --> 00:45:15,920
Boss: Well, there are trucks for export


1141
00:45:15,920 --> 00:45:19,330
exporting to Africa and other places


1142
00:45:19,330 --> 00:45:21,270
There are also National Standard 1 and 2


1143
00:45:21,270 --> 00:45:22,990
and European Standard 1 and 2 and 0 as well


1144
00:45:22,990 --> 00:45:24,090
And some African ones


1145
00:45:24,090 --> 00:45:26,930
But your trucks have National Standard 4 labels on them


1146
00:45:26,930 --> 00:45:31,430
Well... perhaps they... export... like if they export


1147
00:45:31,430 --> 00:45:32,520
They are sold for export


1148
00:45:32,520 --> 00:45:37,120
Ummm... so that's how it happened


1149
00:45:37,120 --> 00:45:39,010
You mean you put the wrong labels on by mistake?


1150
00:45:39,920 --> 00:45:41,980
Yeah, maybe they stuck, stuck, something of their own


1151
00:45:41,980 --> 00:45:43,110
Someone wants the cars


1152
00:45:43,110 --> 00:45:45,120
So, so, so, we sold them (laughter)


1153
00:45:45,580 --> 00:45:47,900
I don’t know how our African brothers would feel after hearing this


1154
00:45:47,900 --> 00:45:50,340
A business always has its rationalizations


1155
00:45:50,340 --> 00:45:51,460
and reasons


1156
00:45:51,460 --> 00:45:53,420
But what makes me curious is


1157
00:45:53,420 --> 00:45:54,420
for more than ten years


1158
00:45:54,420 --> 00:45:56,780
if such fake manufacturers are so common and widespread,


1159
00:45:56,780 --> 00:45:58,100
and are known by the supervisory departments


1160
00:45:58,100 --> 00:45:59,540
why aren't they dealt with?


1161
00:45:59,540 --> 00:46:01,020
Don’t we have laws?


1162
00:46:01,020 --> 00:46:03,140
Don’t we have regulations


1163
00:46:03,140 --> 00:46:04,380
to recall defective automotive products?


1164
00:46:04,380 --> 00:46:06,300
Such products can surely be recalled, can't they?


1165
00:46:06,300 --> 00:46:08,260
However, from 2004 to today


1166
00:46:08,260 --> 00:46:09,620
how many times has this law been applied


1167
00:46:09,620 --> 00:46:11,740
to these kinds of vehicles?


1168
00:46:11,740 --> 00:46:12,860
Not even once


1169
00:46:12,860 --> 00:46:13,780
Why?


1170
00:46:13,780 --> 00:46:15,580
This is the answer I got


1171
00:46:15,580 --> 00:46:16,980
only when the defects pose unreasonable danger


1172
00:46:16,980 --> 00:46:19,740
toward the safety of people or their property


1173
00:46:19,740 --> 00:46:22,020
can the product be recalled


1174
00:46:22,020 --> 00:46:23,060
They say


1175
00:46:23,060 --> 00:46:24,100
leaving environmental protection devices out of manufacturing


1176
00:46:24,100 --> 00:46:25,020
has nothing to do with safety


1177
00:46:25,020 --> 00:46:26,540
It won’t kill anyone


1178
00:46:26,540 --> 00:46:29,100
so there’s no reason for a recall


1179
00:46:29,100 --> 00:46:31,660
Then do we have the right to fine the manufacturers or make them destroy their products?


1180
00:46:31,660 --> 00:46:32,500
We do


1181
00:46:32,500 --> 00:46:34,340
The “Atmospheric Pollution Prevention Act” states that:


1182
00:46:34,340 --> 00:46:36,100
You can make these factories stop their illegal production


1183
00:46:36,100 --> 00:46:36,620
You can fine them


1184
00:46:36,620 --> 00:46:38,100
You can also confiscate and destroy their products


1185
00:46:38,100 --> 00:46:40,940
More than ten years have passed since 2002


1186
00:46:40,940 --> 00:46:43,580
How many times has this law been used?


1187
00:46:43,580 --> 00:46:46,300
Not even once


1188
00:46:46,300 --> 00:46:47,180
Why?


1189
00:46:47,180 --> 00:46:48,700
This is the answer I got


1190
00:46:48,700 --> 00:46:53,500
This law can only be enforced by the departments with the legal right of supervision


1191
00:46:53,500 --> 00:46:54,740
Everyone says


1192
00:46:54,740 --> 00:46:57,660
I don’t know which department that is


1193
00:46:57,660 --> 00:47:00,140
Since there are only a few departments related to automotive management


1194
00:47:00,140 --> 00:47:01,540
I just called them one by one


1195
00:47:01,540 --> 00:47:04,220
First I asked the Ministry of Environmental Protection


1196
00:47:04,220 --> 00:47:05,620
They said:


1197
00:47:05,620 --> 00:47:08,340
As far as we know, it’s not us


1198
00:47:08,340 --> 00:47:10,060
Then I asked the Ministry of Industry and Information Technology


1199
00:47:10,060 --> 00:47:13,260
They say: It’s definitely not us


1200
00:47:13,260 --> 00:47:15,900
Then I asked the General Administration of Quality Supervision and Inspection, they said:


1201
00:47:15,900 --> 00:47:18,540
It should be all three of us


1202
00:47:18,540 --> 00:47:20,380
I think they do have a reason to be confused


1203
00:47:20,380 --> 00:47:21,620
Why doesn’t the law


1204
00:47:21,620 --> 00:47:24,060
just clarify who is in charge of this management?


1205
00:47:24,060 --> 00:47:25,820
I had to turn to the National People’s Congress


1206
00:47:25,820 --> 00:47:27,540
So I called the NPC


1207
00:47:27,540 --> 00:47:29,500
And this was their reply:


1208
00:47:29,500 --> 00:47:33,340
The issue of this law's execution is indeed unclear


1209
00:47:33,340 --> 00:47:35,540
This is a very rare case in our legislative process


1210
00:47:35,540 --> 00:47:38,990
Why would it exist nowhere else but in Article 53 of the Law on Atmosphere?


1211
00:47:38,990 --> 00:47:40,170
Ding Yan - Director of MEP Vehicular Pollution Research Institute


1212
00:47:40,170 --> 00:47:40,820
We asked them (NPC) back then


1213
00:47:40,820 --> 00:47:42,340
Why did you write the Law on Atmosphere like this?


1214
00:47:42,340 --> 00:47:43,420
Why don’t you just let us take charge of it?


1215
00:47:43,420 --> 00:47:45,820
They replied that because when they were making this law


1216
00:47:45,820 --> 00:47:47,260
many departments opposed it


1217
00:47:47,260 --> 00:47:48,300
saying that the MEP should not be in charge


1218
00:47:48,300 --> 00:47:50,140
so the bill could not pass


1219
00:47:50,140 --> 00:47:53,140
In the end the NPC had to use a vague term to make it pass


1220
00:47:53,140 --> 00:47:55,220
So it says that only departments with executive authority can enforce this law


1221
00:47:55,220 --> 00:47:57,260
It sounds like all three departments are responsible for supervision


1222
00:47:57,260 --> 00:47:58,780
But in reality we cannot control it


1223
00:47:58,780 --> 00:47:59,820
Their certificates are all valid


1224
00:47:59,820 --> 00:48:01,140
so are the vehicles' types


1225
00:48:01,140 --> 00:48:02,780
The MEP issues them green labels


1226
00:48:02,780 --> 00:48:03,700
of National Standard 4


1227
00:48:03,700 --> 00:48:05,740
but not a single department actually goes out and looks at the cars


1228
00:48:05,740 --> 00:48:07,340
which are in fact only up to Standard 1


1229
00:48:07,340 --> 00:48:09,620
If you (at the MEP) assert you have legal authority, no one can deny that


1230
00:48:09,620 --> 00:48:10,540
So why don't you just execute the law?


1231
00:48:10,540 --> 00:48:13,820
The MEP is indeed suspected of not doing its best, I admit this


1232
00:48:13,820 --> 00:48:16,020
The situation is that we didn’t pursue this issue further


1233
00:48:16,020 --> 00:48:18,900
So after so many years your law enforcement powers are still completely toothless?


1234
00:48:18,900 --> 00:48:21,940
Nowadays I don't dare open my mouth out of fear that people will see I have no teeth.


1235
00:48:21,940 --> 00:48:23,140
That’s the awkward thing about the MEP's situation.


1236
00:48:25,380 --> 00:48:26,780
This isn't just awkward for the MEP


1237
00:48:26,780 --> 00:48:28,140
Truck companies are also in an awkward position


1238
00:48:28,140 --> 00:48:30,380
The truck company with fake emissions stickers said


1239
00:48:30,380 --> 00:48:32,820
If the MEP can enforce the law


1240
00:48:32,820 --> 00:48:34,300
and impound those “fake” trucks


1241
00:48:34,300 --> 00:48:36,460
I guarantee we would build “real” trucks the very next day


1242
00:48:36,700 --> 00:48:37,820
Otherwise, if we build "real" trucks


1243
00:48:37,820 --> 00:48:38,780
and others build "fake" trucks


1244
00:48:38,780 --> 00:48:40,220
we would be bankrupt tomorrow


1245
00:48:40,220 --> 00:48:43,060
So I asked Ding Yan, do you think this perspective is reasonable?


1246
00:48:43,060 --> 00:48:44,140
He said “Yes”


1247
00:48:44,140 --> 00:48:46,900
Not enforcing the law forces people to cheat


1248
00:48:47,900 --> 00:48:49,540
The truck company owner also said


1249
00:48:49,540 --> 00:48:53,860
National Standard 4 has already been set and it applies to all new vehicles


1250
00:48:53,860 --> 00:48:56,340
But National Standard 4 compliant fuel is still scarce


1251
00:48:56,340 --> 00:48:58,900
and the fuel quality is not as high as it should be


1252
00:48:58,900 --> 00:49:00,580
When we were in Yanqing


1253
00:49:00,580 --> 00:49:03,060
and randomly checked this diesel truck


1254
00:49:03,060 --> 00:49:04,700
The diesel gas came from Beijing


1255
00:49:04,700 --> 00:49:07,460
and was expected to be of high quality, the highest level in China


1256
00:49:07,460 --> 00:49:09,460
But when the diesel test results came out,


1257
00:49:09,460 --> 00:49:13,100
the (sulfur content) was 25 times higher than European, Japanese, and US diesel


1258
00:49:13,100 --> 00:49:14,620
That's the top level of quality


1259
00:49:14,620 --> 00:49:17,380
What about the quality of our gasoline?


1260
00:49:17,380 --> 00:49:20,500
This is a table I got from Chinese Research Academy of Environmental Science


1261
00:49:20,500 --> 00:49:22,580
This table pains me every time I look at it


1262
00:49:22,580 --> 00:49:24,540
because I cannot understand it at all


1263
00:49:24,540 --> 00:49:26,260
Fortunately they gave me the conclusion


1264
00:49:26,260 --> 00:49:28,220
This shows our national fuel quality is


1265
00:49:28,220 --> 00:49:30,860
normally two or three grades lower than fuel found in developed countries.


1266
00:49:30,860 --> 00:49:32,300
If we can raise our national fuel quality by just one grade


1267
00:49:32,300 --> 00:49:34,140
we can reduce emissions by 10%


1268
00:49:34,140 --> 00:49:35,860
It seems like we have some good fuel available in China


1269
00:49:35,860 --> 00:49:37,380
We have Standard 4 and higher quality fuel


1270
00:49:37,380 --> 00:49:39,980
but these only make up 3% of China's total fuels


1271
00:49:39,980 --> 00:49:41,820
This is Hangzhou's problem


1272
00:49:41,820 --> 00:49:43,180
Hangzhou has money and


1273
00:49:43,180 --> 00:49:44,380
wants to buy high quality fuel


1274
00:49:44,380 --> 00:49:46,580
But until 2013 there was no high quality fuel available


1275
00:49:46,580 --> 00:49:47,980
Even after a huge effort


1276
00:49:47,980 --> 00:49:50,220
the best you can manage is Standard 3 fuel


1277
00:49:50,220 --> 00:49:52,460
Even in Beijing, it looks like our sulfur content


1278
00:49:52,460 --> 00:49:53,580
is on the same level as Europe's


1279
00:49:53,580 --> 00:49:55,060
on the same level as America's


1280
00:49:55,060 --> 00:49:57,220
But look at the four items in this box


1281
00:49:57,220 --> 00:50:01,260
These cryptic figures carry a hidden danger


1282
00:50:01,260 --> 00:50:01,980
They either


1283
00:50:01,980 --> 00:50:03,060
increase oxidants in the atmosphere


1284
00:50:03,060 --> 00:50:03,980
creating more fine particulates


1285
00:50:03,980 --> 00:50:05,460
or increase toxicity


1286
00:50:05,460 --> 00:50:07,100
The last item is increasing evaporative pressure


1287
00:50:07,100 --> 00:50:10,780
It increases the rate of gasoline evaporation into the air


1288
00:50:10,780 --> 00:50:13,540
I originally thought, really, how much can it possibly evaporate?


1289
00:50:13,540 --> 00:50:15,340
Then the CRAES expert told me


1290
00:50:15,340 --> 00:50:16,620
look at this clip


1291
00:50:16,620 --> 00:50:18,620
This is filmed with an infrared camera


1292
00:50:18,620 --> 00:50:19,660
If gas stations don’t install


1293
00:50:19,660 --> 00:50:21,260
a part on the nozzle to recapture gasoline vapor


1294
00:50:21,260 --> 00:50:23,460
then this is how much can evaporate


1295
00:50:23,460 --> 00:50:27,460
1.5 grams for each liter of gasoline will go into our atmosphere


1296
00:50:27,460 --> 00:50:31,100
The gas in the tanks of the cars we all drive also evaporates in the same way


1297
00:50:31,100 --> 00:50:32,580
How strong is the evaporative power?


1298
00:50:32,580 --> 00:50:37,060
In Beijing, more airborne hydrocarbons come from evaporation


1299
00:50:37,060 --> 00:50:42,020
than from car emissions


1300
00:50:42,020 --> 00:50:45,460
And these substances are a major component of PM2.5


1301
00:50:45,460 --> 00:50:48,940
So why don’t we make the fuel cleaner right away?


1302
00:50:48,940 --> 00:50:52,620
The petrochemical industry told us this


1303
00:50:52,620 --> 00:50:55,260
“The national standard is set too low.”


1304
00:50:55,260 --> 00:50:57,220
This sentence seems reasonable


1305
00:50:57,220 --> 00:50:59,260
How could you reasonably require companies to produce


1306
00:50:59,260 --> 00:51:01,220
fuel that's better than the official standard? Right?


1307
00:51:01,220 --> 00:51:04,140
Then I asked the MEP and CRAES


1308
00:51:04,140 --> 00:51:06,060
the people involved in setting the standard


1309
00:51:06,060 --> 00:51:08,180
Why don't you set the standard higher?


1310
00:51:08,180 --> 00:51:09,300
This is the answer he gave me


1311
00:51:09,300 --> 00:51:10,940
The standards subcommittee (Petroleum Fuel and Lubricant Technology Committee)


1312
00:51:10,940 --> 00:51:13,100
Is actually mostly... yes, mostly made up of


1313
00:51:13,100 --> 00:51:14,500
people from the oil industry


1314
00:51:14,500 --> 00:51:17,180
About 67%


1315
00:51:17,180 --> 00:51:18,700
The full standards committee (National Petroleum Fuel and Lubricant Technology Committee)


1316
00:51:18,700 --> 00:51:19,980
has even more, in the full committee, it's almost...


1317
00:51:19,980 --> 00:51:22,580
over 90%, as I recall are people from this industry


1318
00:51:22,580 --> 00:51:24,900
The secretariat of the full committee is also located in the petrochemical industry


1319
00:51:24,900 --> 00:51:27,140
Then the head of this standards committee


1320
00:51:27,140 --> 00:51:28,660
He's also a member of the petrochemical industry


1321
00:51:28,660 --> 00:51:29,660
I used to think


1322
00:51:29,660 --> 00:51:31,780
you guys (in Environmental Protection) had a veto right


1323
00:51:32,940 --> 00:51:34,380
Yeah, you'd think so, right?


1324
00:51:34,380 --> 00:51:35,580
(Since we're in) environmental protection?


1325
00:51:36,380 --> 00:51:38,060
This dark joke from Yue Xin


1326
00:51:38,060 --> 00:51:40,340
left a very deep impression on me


1327
00:51:40,340 --> 00:51:42,300
He said, “The only time I felt like I even existed


1328
00:51:42,300 --> 00:51:43,380
was when I came in the door


1329
00:51:43,380 --> 00:51:45,540
and I wrote my name on the sign-in sheet


1330
00:51:45,540 --> 00:51:47,860
Because before, I didn’t even have a vote.”


1331
00:51:47,860 --> 00:51:49,580
He said he and his colleagues will do everything they can


1332
00:51:49,580 --> 00:51:50,980
to push for better fuel quality


1333
00:51:50,980 --> 00:51:54,020
But the oil fuel industry has always explained it like this:


1334
00:51:54,020 --> 00:51:55,620
Most of the fuel in our country


1335
00:51:55,620 --> 00:51:57,340
is imported from the Middle East, right?


1336
00:51:57,340 --> 00:52:00,140
Well then, most oil from Iran, for example, is high in sulphur


1337
00:52:00,140 --> 00:52:02,580
In Tehran, they themselves are also facing


1338
00:52:02,580 --> 00:52:05,140
problems caused by poor-quality fuel


1339
00:52:05,140 --> 00:52:07,020
The smog there is severe


1340
00:52:07,020 --> 00:52:08,180
But Iran's problem is


1341
00:52:08,180 --> 00:52:10,700
they don’t have the skills to improve fuel quality


1342
00:52:10,700 --> 00:52:13,500
Chinese companies, on the other hand, do have these techniques


1343
00:52:13,500 --> 00:52:15,100
Where is the split between government and industry?


1344
00:52:15,100 --> 00:52:16,780
Money


1345
00:52:16,780 --> 00:52:18,100
From Standard 3 to Standard 4


1346
00:52:18,100 --> 00:52:21,620
the MEP says 7 cents per liter is enough


1347
00:52:21,620 --> 00:52:22,620
The industry says: no


1348
00:52:22,620 --> 00:52:24,100
Give me 50 cents


1349
00:52:24,100 --> 00:52:25,780
I say, both of you can sit down and show the expenses


1350
00:52:25,780 --> 00:52:26,580
and calculate it


1351
00:52:26,580 --> 00:52:29,180
Calculate how much it would be, it's a simple thing


1352
00:52:29,180 --> 00:52:30,660
He had another wry smile


1353
00:52:30,660 --> 00:52:33,260
Don’t say it's me, go ask the National Development and Reform Commission Economic Department


1354
00:52:33,260 --> 00:52:34,860
and see if they know


1355
00:52:34,860 --> 00:52:35,620
(Source: Anonymous NDRC official)


1356
00:52:35,620 --> 00:52:36,660
You can't control it.


1357
00:52:36,660 --> 00:52:38,100
Say you have an only child


1358
00:52:38,100 --> 00:52:39,420
And this child is learning bad behavior


1359
00:52:39,420 --> 00:52:41,300
As his mother, what can you do?


1360
00:52:41,300 --> 00:52:42,980
All you can do is give him one good beating


1361
00:52:42,980 --> 00:52:44,740
You can't  beat him everyday


1362
00:52:44,740 --> 00:52:45,900
Somebody else may have 10 kids


1363
00:52:45,900 --> 00:52:47,380
they won't make trouble


1364
00:52:47,380 --> 00:52:48,620
They are right in front of you


1365
00:52:48,620 --> 00:52:49,900
They don’t pay us any mind


1366
00:52:49,900 --> 00:52:50,780
These deputy-level units


1367
00:52:50,780 --> 00:52:51,940
What can you do about it?


1368
00:52:51,940 --> 00:52:52,780
Are they going to pay any mind to you?


1369
00:52:52,780 --> 00:52:54,420
If your price department doesn't raise the price this year


1370
00:52:54,420 --> 00:52:55,260
next year they'll be at your door


1371
00:52:55,260 --> 00:52:55,940
Are you going to raise it or not?


1372
00:52:55,940 --> 00:52:56,860
If you don't, I'll cut off the supply


1373
00:52:56,860 --> 00:52:57,460
That's what they say


1374
00:53:00,900 --> 00:53:04,780
I didn't know whether to trust these things the MEP and NDRC said


1375
00:53:04,780 --> 00:53:05,540
Is it the truth?


1376
00:53:05,540 --> 00:53:06,580
Does it have any basis in reality?


1377
00:53:06,580 --> 00:53:07,700
So I had to verify it


1378
00:53:07,700 --> 00:53:10,780
I reached out to the Head of the National Oil Fuel Standard Committee


1379
00:53:10,780 --> 00:53:13,980
and former Chief Engineer at China Petrochemical Corporation (Sinopec)


1380
00:53:13,980 --> 00:53:14,980
Mr. Cao Xianghong


1381
00:53:14,980 --> 00:53:16,220
Asking if I can meet him to chat


1382
00:53:16,220 --> 00:53:17,860
And ask a few questions


1383
00:53:17,860 --> 00:53:19,140
He agreed


1384
00:53:21,030 --> 00:53:23,580
First Question: Why has the process of setting fuel standards been led by the oil industry?


1385
00:53:23,580 --> 00:53:26,700
If the majority of participants come from industry


1386
00:53:26,700 --> 00:53:29,740
This might be against the best interest of the public


1387
00:53:29,740 --> 00:53:32,740
When convening a committee to set petroleum product standards


1388
00:53:32,740 --> 00:53:34,300
You shouldn't be looking for


1389
00:53:34,300 --> 00:53:36,700
someone who doesn't understand the oil refining business


1390
00:53:36,700 --> 00:53:38,820
People from the MEP don’t understand it?


1391
00:53:38,820 --> 00:53:40,500
The MEP, no, I don't believe they understand


1392
00:53:40,720 --> 00:53:43,140
Second Question: Who should set the standard?


1393
00:53:43,220 --> 00:53:44,700
If you set a standard


1394
00:53:44,700 --> 00:53:47,140
then when the time comes to improve it, you say it's impossible


1395
00:53:47,140 --> 00:53:49,100
Then when the deadline arrives, you say you cannot provide fuel


1396
00:53:49,100 --> 00:53:52,740
Now you may have all sorts of reasons for this, but people may not believe you


1397
00:53:52,740 --> 00:53:54,540
But if Sinopec doesn’t take the lead in drafting this


1398
00:53:54,540 --> 00:53:56,180
who else is there to draft it?


1399
00:53:56,180 --> 00:53:57,420
Well, for example, in some countries


1400
00:53:57,420 --> 00:53:59,380
first, their environmental protection agencies have people who understand the industry


1401
00:53:59,380 --> 00:54:00,100
Yes


1402
00:54:00,100 --> 00:54:02,300
Second, before they submit the draft


1403
00:54:02,300 --> 00:54:06,820
they take plenty of time with industry people to understand, communicate and debate


1404
00:54:07,460 --> 00:54:12,780
At the very end, their health reports, economic reports, these are all provided in full to the committee


1405
00:54:12,780 --> 00:54:14,500
And then through an open, public process


1406
00:54:14,500 --> 00:54:15,860
They let everyone judge it for themselves


1407
00:54:15,860 --> 00:54:19,300
And they all have opportunities to express their opinions and debate with one another


1408
00:54:19,300 --> 00:54:22,300
If it's done with this method, do you think you could consider accepting that?


1409
00:54:22,300 --> 00:54:23,700
I could accept that


1410
00:54:23,700 --> 00:54:26,180
I've wanted to give up this Standards Committee chairmanship for quite a long time


1411
00:54:26,180 --> 00:54:26,660
Really?


1412
00:54:26,660 --> 00:54:27,300
Really


1413
00:54:27,300 --> 00:54:29,820
People on the outside say, “You're too partial to Sinopec.”


1414
00:54:29,820 --> 00:54:32,300
But then Sinopec says, “Stop biting the hand that feeds you.”


1415
00:54:32,300 --> 00:54:33,540
You can't satisfy everyone


1416
00:54:33,540 --> 00:54:36,160
Third Question: Why won't you publicize the costs of upgrading our fuel?


1417
00:54:36,220 --> 00:54:40,060
Can you publish either your input costs or upgrade costs?


1418
00:54:40,060 --> 00:54:40,980
Show it to the public?


1419
00:54:40,980 --> 00:54:43,180
In society nowadays, naturally when it comes to


1420
00:54:43,180 --> 00:54:45,460
Sinopec, or the China National Petroleum Corporation


1421
00:54:45,460 --> 00:54:47,540
People have a feeling of mistrust


1422
00:54:47,540 --> 00:54:48,900
Do you feel this mistrust–


1423
00:54:48,900 --> 00:54:50,500
Many people don’t bother with rational discussion


1424
00:54:50,500 --> 00:54:52,900
If there is some tiny flaw, they will blow it up into something huge


1425
00:54:52,900 --> 00:54:54,660
It just makes matters worse


1426
00:54:54,660 --> 00:54:56,060
It's better to not say anything at all


1427
00:54:56,230 --> 00:54:58,900
Fourth Question: Can we raise the standard and force a fuel upgrade?


1428
00:54:58,940 --> 00:55:01,780
Many people will say why don’t we raise the standard a bit


1429
00:55:01,780 --> 00:55:04,780
and force improvement in the fuel quality?


1430
00:55:04,780 --> 00:55:07,300
If there were an interruption to the fuel supply


1431
00:55:07,300 --> 00:55:08,940
resulting in social instability


1432
00:55:08,940 --> 00:55:10,220
There would be turmoil in our society


1433
00:55:10,220 --> 00:55:13,740
Then would it be possible to fully open the market for finished petroleum products?


1434
00:55:13,740 --> 00:55:15,940
That would eliminate the possibility of interruptions to the fuel supply


1435
00:55:15,940 --> 00:55:18,380
If it wasn't done right, it could be a disaster


1436
00:55:18,380 --> 00:55:20,740
Not every Tom, Dick, and Harry can run a fuel company


1437
00:55:20,740 --> 00:55:21,580
Then he might think


1438
00:55:21,580 --> 00:55:23,740
why can only Sinopec and CNPC make money?


1439
00:55:23,740 --> 00:55:25,060
Everybody else can make money too


1440
00:55:25,060 --> 00:55:26,540
Yes, everybody can make money


1441
00:55:26,540 --> 00:55:31,060
So I agree with deepening reform and gradual opening up


1442
00:55:31,060 --> 00:55:32,220
If the government wants to decide


1443
00:55:32,220 --> 00:55:33,740
and push through this kind of reform


1444
00:55:33,740 --> 00:55:35,140
Then the government should go do some research first


1445
00:55:35,140 --> 00:55:36,860
and find out what kind of risks there might be


1446
00:55:36,860 --> 00:55:39,950
Fifth Question: Can [oil companies] take on more social responsibility?


1447
00:55:40,020 --> 00:55:40,780
Many people will say


1448
00:55:40,780 --> 00:55:44,500
Sinopec is already a Fortune 500 global company


1449
00:55:44,500 --> 00:55:47,780
It's just announced an income of 2 trillion RMB ($319 billion) last year


1450
00:55:47,780 --> 00:55:51,220
It's a large state-owned company


1451
00:55:51,220 --> 00:55:53,420
So, when it comes to environmental issues


1452
00:55:53,420 --> 00:55:56,900
why can't it take on more of its own social responsibility?


1453
00:55:59,300 --> 00:56:01,340
Sinopec is huge


1454
00:56:01,340 --> 00:56:03,140
Like a person


1455
00:56:03,140 --> 00:56:04,740
Very big


1456
00:56:04,740 --> 00:56:06,180
But it's all fat and no muscle


1457
00:56:06,820 --> 00:56:08,980
Petroleum companies all over the world


1458
00:56:08,980 --> 00:56:11,780
will try to protect the interests of their industry


1459
00:56:11,780 --> 00:56:13,260
That's the nature of a corporation


1460
00:56:13,260 --> 00:56:14,700
and it's not going to change


1461
00:56:14,700 --> 00:56:15,660
We wanted to know


1462
00:56:15,660 --> 00:56:17,900
in other countries, who sets the fuel standards?


1463
00:56:17,900 --> 00:56:21,500
This is our conclusion so far:


1464
00:56:21,500 --> 00:56:25,340
In Australia, Korea, Japan, Mexico, and Canada


1465
00:56:25,340 --> 00:56:27,820
Environmental agencies are basically in charge of setting the standards


1466
00:56:27,820 --> 00:56:28,900
Even in the European Union,


1467
00:56:28,900 --> 00:56:30,300
where it is decided by the European Standards Committee


1468
00:56:30,300 --> 00:56:32,220
they hear from industry associations


1469
00:56:32,220 --> 00:56:36,340
But there's never been a case when the petrochemical industry actually led the standards process


1470
00:56:37,620 --> 00:56:42,540
But why are fuel quality standards in China set by the oil industry?


1471
00:56:42,540 --> 00:56:45,460
Each country's choice is rooted in its history


1472
00:56:45,460 --> 00:56:49,020
In the 1960s, China was facing an extreme gasoline shortage


1473
00:56:49,020 --> 00:56:50,580
Buses on Chang'an Street, the busiest street in Beijing


1474
00:56:50,580 --> 00:56:52,940
had to carry a big bag of diesel fuel on the roof during operation


1475
00:56:52,940 --> 00:56:55,820
We were a long way from worrying about environmental standards for gasoline


1476
00:56:55,820 --> 00:56:57,460
At the time, the MEP didn't exist


1477
00:56:57,460 --> 00:57:03,060
so the Petrochemical Research Institute under the Ministry of Petroleum regulated fuel standards


1478
00:57:03,060 --> 00:57:05,020
In 1983 as part of institutional reforms


1479
00:57:05,020 --> 00:57:06,300
the Ministry of Petroleum was dissolved


1480
00:57:06,300 --> 00:57:08,900
and the Petrochemical Research Institute became a department of Sinopec


1481
00:57:08,900 --> 00:57:11,220
With that, the government ministry's role in regulating fuel standards


1482
00:57:11,220 --> 00:57:12,460
was handed over to a corporation


1483
00:57:12,460 --> 00:57:15,460
In the year 2005, the first Chinese Petrochemical Standards Committee was founded


1484
00:57:15,460 --> 00:57:18,220
and the oil industry naturally took on a leading role in the group


1485
00:57:18,220 --> 00:57:20,660
For the past ten years China has been faced with


1486
00:57:20,660 --> 00:57:23,060
soaring needs for both fuel quality and fuel quantity


1487
00:57:23,060 --> 00:57:24,580
China faces an unprecedented challenge


1488
00:57:24,580 --> 00:57:26,340
with pressing needs in both respects


1489
00:57:26,340 --> 00:57:27,380
As the Chinese economy develops further


1490
00:57:27,380 --> 00:57:28,940
environmental protection is receiving more attention


1491
00:57:28,940 --> 00:57:32,220
With the Chinese public calling for higher fuel standards


1492
00:57:32,220 --> 00:57:34,900
real changes have been made within the CPSC


1493
00:57:34,900 --> 00:57:37,740
Although members from the oil industries still make up over half of the committee


1494
00:57:37,740 --> 00:57:39,660
the number of members from outside the oil industry


1495
00:57:39,660 --> 00:57:41,620
has increased during the past two years


1496
00:57:41,620 --> 00:57:43,860
The committee has also set up a voting system


1497
00:57:43,860 --> 00:57:45,500
In the end, each country's standards for oil and gasoline quality


1498
00:57:45,500 --> 00:57:50,020
emerge from balancing the needs of the economy and the environment


1499
00:57:50,020 --> 00:57:53,380
Future changes to the CPSC will emerge from this balancing act


1500
00:57:57,380 --> 00:58:00,420
In China, in addition to the low oil standards


1501
00:58:00,420 --> 00:58:04,460
there is another problem that I could never have imagined before I started out


1502
00:58:04,460 --> 00:58:08,820
That is, half of the oil in China is completely unregulated


1503
00:58:08,820 --> 00:58:12,900
Out of the world’s top ten ports, seven are in China


1504
00:58:12,900 --> 00:58:15,740
Ocean-going cargo vessels cause so much pollution


1505
00:58:15,740 --> 00:58:17,820
that  within 400 meters of the coast


1506
00:58:17,820 --> 00:58:20,980
emissions from ships are equivalent to emissions from 500,000 trucks


1507
00:58:20,980 --> 00:58:25,460
So, in Shenzhen, 60% of the sulfur dioxide is from ships


1508
00:58:25,460 --> 00:58:28,900
Maybe you don’t live by a harbor, but you do live by a river


1509
00:58:28,900 --> 00:58:30,860
There are more than 200,000 boats like this in China


1510
00:58:30,860 --> 00:58:34,140
burning heavy oil of the lowest quality


1511
00:58:34,140 --> 00:58:35,620
How polluting can it get?


1512
00:58:35,620 --> 00:58:37,580
At some harbors, you can even pick up


1513
00:58:37,580 --> 00:58:38,980
grains of black carbon with your hand


1514
00:58:38,980 --> 00:58:41,460
Or maybe you live near an airport


1515
00:58:41,460 --> 00:58:43,820
When a plane takes off, that's one ton of kerosene burned


1516
00:58:43,820 --> 00:58:46,020
and when it lands, that's another ton


1517
00:58:46,020 --> 00:58:47,580
So at Baiyun Airport in Guangzhou


1518
00:58:47,580 --> 00:58:50,860
the daily emissions are equivalent to emissions from 600,000 taxis


1519
00:58:52,460 --> 00:58:56,580
Maybe you don’t live by a harbor, along a river, or near an airport


1520
00:58:56,580 --> 00:58:58,900
but you've certainly seen vehicles like this


1521
00:58:58,900 --> 00:59:01,060
These are construction vehicles


1522
00:59:01,060 --> 00:59:02,860
Once in Hebei province I saw one of these


1523
00:59:02,860 --> 00:59:04,860
and I thought something up ahead was on fire


1524
00:59:04,860 --> 00:59:06,140
When I overtook it on the road


1525
00:59:06,140 --> 00:59:07,620
I realized it was the source of that black smoke


1526
00:59:07,620 --> 00:59:10,320
Then we followed it into a village


1527
00:59:10,320 --> 00:59:11,770
The entrance of the village looked like this


1528
00:59:11,770 --> 00:59:12,900
(Sign: Diesel)


1529
00:59:12,900 --> 00:59:18,020
We saw a small room at the entrance with villagers playing mahjong and selling lottery tickets


1530
00:59:18,020 --> 00:59:20,300
They sold diesel and coal slurry, too


1531
00:59:20,300 --> 00:59:22,500
I had no idea where the diesel came from


1532
00:59:22,500 --> 00:59:24,500
I was with some officials from the MEP


1533
00:59:24,500 --> 00:59:28,100
and they suggested we should go investigate


1534
00:59:28,100 --> 00:59:30,580
So they bought a diesel can on the spot


1535
00:59:30,580 --> 00:59:33,700
and then went into the nearest privately-owned gas station


1536
00:59:33,700 --> 00:59:36,180
I was the last one out of the car and by the time I got out


1537
00:59:36,180 --> 00:59:38,580
the official's government ID had already been taken away by the owner


1538
00:59:39,840 --> 00:59:42,970
Station Owner: You… you guys… what do you want…


1539
00:59:42,970 --> 00:59:44,980
I’m… I’m not giving (your ID) back


1540
00:59:44,980 --> 00:59:46,910
Environment Officer: (We are from) the EPB enforcement.


1541
00:59:46,910 --> 00:59:48,160
EPB enforcement? What are you doing here?


1542
00:59:48,160 --> 00:59:49,570
This is a random inspection.


1543
00:59:49,570 --> 00:59:51,120
You… You want to inspect? Inspect what...?


1544
00:59:51,120 --> 00:59:53,000
No… What right do you EPB guys have to take samples for investigation…


1545
00:59:53,000 --> 00:59:54,000
EPB… do... do… do... do you even have...?


1546
00:59:54,000 --> 00:59:55,120
We're going to run a test.


1547
00:59:55,120 --> 00:59:56,810
No no no... You EPB guys have... what is this...


1548
00:59:56,810 --> 00:59:58,930
Yes, yes, of course we have the authority to monitor diesel quality


1549
00:59:58,930 --> 00:59:59,940
there is… the Technical Monitoring Authority…


1550
00:59:59,940 --> 01:00:01,980
Diesel Quality Monitoring Authority… governed by the (Oil) Union Authority


1551
01:00:01,980 --> 01:00:02,980
The EPB has [the authority] too


1552
01:00:02,980 --> 01:00:04,980
Environmental Protection… This is the first time I’ve heard of it, what does the EPB care?


1553
01:00:04,980 --> 01:00:07,830
Let me tell you… you… take… take… take the sample… take a prepared sample


1554
01:00:07,830 --> 01:00:10,680
Yes… there is this… Technical Monitoring Authority… there is this… that...


1555
01:00:10,680 --> 01:00:12,440
Yes… there's the “Air Pollution Prevention Act”


1556
01:00:12,440 --> 01:00:13,730
“Air Pollution Prevention Act?”


1557
01:00:13,730 --> 01:00:15,220
“The EPB has the authority and obligation…”


1558
01:00:15,220 --> 01:00:17,460
You… have the obligation… you have the obligation, but not the authority


1559
01:00:19,020 --> 01:00:21,060
When the owner finished that sentence


1560
01:00:21,060 --> 01:00:22,740
each of us was left speechless


1561
01:00:22,740 --> 01:00:26,100
All we could do was take our diesel can and leave


1562
01:00:26,100 --> 01:00:28,380
He'd put it so ruthlessly


1563
01:00:28,380 --> 01:00:30,900
From coal, to oil, and on down the list


1564
01:00:30,900 --> 01:00:33,580
We consume so much coal and oil


1565
01:00:33,580 --> 01:00:36,620
Our coal and oil quality is relatively low


1566
01:00:36,620 --> 01:00:38,020
We don't do enough to clean it


1567
01:00:38,020 --> 01:00:41,020
and when we emit, we don't regulate that enough either


1568
01:00:41,020 --> 01:00:43,300
All along, I have wanted to know why


1569
01:00:43,300 --> 01:00:44,820
until this gas station owner


1570
01:00:44,820 --> 01:00:47,660
Without even realizing it himself, in a single sentence


1571
01:00:47,660 --> 01:00:49,340
cut straight to the heart of the matter


1572
01:00:55,420 --> 01:00:56,300
Less than half of our coal is washed


1573
01:00:56,300 --> 01:00:57,140
There are no restrictions


1574
01:00:57,140 --> 01:00:57,860
There are no standards


1575
01:00:57,860 --> 01:00:59,020
There are no national regulations


1576
01:00:59,200 --> 01:01:00,090
Requirements for coal washing: none


1577
01:01:00,140 --> 01:01:02,460
What about the steel industry in Hebei?


1578
01:01:02,460 --> 01:01:05,420
It's reached the point where nothing can stop them


1579
01:01:05,420 --> 01:01:06,260
Polluting companies: unstoppable


1580
01:01:06,260 --> 01:01:08,020
The operators of this truck


1581
01:01:08,020 --> 01:01:08,940
have not been fined


1582
01:01:08,940 --> 01:01:12,020
No penalties have been applied in 14 years? No, never


1583
01:01:12,020 --> 01:01:13,140
Over-emitting vehicles: enforcement responsibility unclear, cannot be recalled


1584
01:01:13,140 --> 01:01:14,900
Over 90% are individuals from the petrochemical industry


1585
01:01:14,900 --> 01:01:17,420
I don’t think the environmental protection authorities understand


1586
01:01:17,420 --> 01:01:18,340
Petroleum standards: unregulatable


1587
01:01:18,340 --> 01:01:19,980
This is the conundrum of environmental protection


1588
01:01:19,980 --> 01:01:21,460
Now I don't dare open my mouth


1589
01:01:21,460 --> 01:01:22,740
I fear that people will notice I have no teeth


1590
01:01:22,740 --> 01:01:24,740
Environmental protection authorities have an obligation and the authority


1591
01:01:24,740 --> 01:01:26,900
You have an obligation, but not the authority


1592
01:01:26,900 --> 01:01:28,900
Petroleum product quality: no inspection authority


1593
01:01:28,900 --> 01:01:30,900
“Isn't that the conundrum of environmental protection?”


1594
01:01:31,020 --> 01:01:35,060
So one night there was an environmental protection professional


1595
01:01:35,060 --> 01:01:36,820
who sent me this photo


1596
01:01:38,860 --> 01:01:41,820
This is a photo taken in 1999


1597
01:01:41,820 --> 01:01:43,220
He graduated from university that year


1598
01:01:43,220 --> 01:01:44,700
He said he was motivated by a calling


1599
01:01:44,700 --> 01:01:46,740
So he went to work for the Environmental Protection Bureau


1600
01:01:46,740 --> 01:01:48,620
He wanted to make a difference


1601
01:01:48,620 --> 01:01:54,740
He said, “Sometimes, I feel like I'm nothing more than a mascot." (laughter)


1602
01:01:54,740 --> 01:01:55,740
So I tried to console him


1603
01:01:55,740 --> 01:01:57,540
I said, “Why do you think so?”


1604
01:01:57,540 --> 01:02:01,380
He said, “You are an investigative reporter


1605
01:02:01,380 --> 01:02:03,580
you must know this better than me”


1606
01:02:03,580 --> 01:02:05,580
2004 interview


1607
01:02:06,540 --> 01:02:09,060
(Suppose) you didn’t get the government approval for land use do you dare to build?


1608
01:02:09,060 --> 01:02:10,420
Ren Baoming - Legal representative, Hongta Coal Washing & Coking Factory


1609
01:02:10,420 --> 01:02:11,380
We wouldn't dare


1610
01:02:11,940 --> 01:02:13,660
Suppose you don’t get the approval from the Administration for Industry and Commerce


1611
01:02:13,660 --> 01:02:14,780
Or the approval from Taxation Bureau


1612
01:02:14,780 --> 01:02:15,540
Do you dare to build?


1613
01:02:15,540 --> 01:02:16,900
No, no


1614
01:02:16,900 --> 01:02:18,500
So why, when you don't have EPB approval, it's all fine?


1615
01:02:18,500 --> 01:02:20,420
We should have EPB approval


1616
01:02:20,420 --> 01:02:20,980
We ought to


1617
01:02:20,980 --> 01:02:21,940
Eventually, we will get it


1618
01:02:22,740 --> 01:02:23,820
Eventually, we will get it


1619
01:02:23,820 --> 01:02:24,540
Exactly


1620
01:02:25,420 --> 01:02:27,440
Did you know about these situations?


1621
01:02:27,440 --> 01:02:28,580
We have taken steps


1622
01:02:28,580 --> 01:02:29,530
Zeng Shumao - Bureau Chief, Environmental Protection Bureau of Xiaoyi City, Shanxi


1623
01:02:29,530 --> 01:02:31,340
On-site checking, inquiries and records


1624
01:02:31,340 --> 01:02:32,860
then impose a penalty


1625
01:02:32,860 --> 01:02:35,740
But the fact is he still went ahead and built, and even went into production


1626
01:02:36,180 --> 01:02:38,300
We finished the procedure that was required


1627
01:02:38,300 --> 01:02:40,100
We issued the Letter of Penalty that was required


1628
01:02:41,180 --> 01:02:43,820
There is nothing we can do if the enterprises do not stop


1629
01:02:43,820 --> 01:02:44,900
This is a kind of helplessness


1630
01:02:44,900 --> 01:02:47,180
Then what you've got here should be considered illegal construction


1631
01:02:47,700 --> 01:02:49,780
Oh well, it's hard to find factories that do not violate regulations


1632
01:02:49,780 --> 01:02:50,940
Zhang Xuguang - Mayor, Xiaoyi City, Shanxi


1633
01:02:50,940 --> 01:02:52,620
The government’s attitude toward coal coking


1634
01:02:52,620 --> 01:02:54,020
We are always cool-headed


1635
01:02:54,020 --> 01:02:55,780
after we took steps


1636
01:02:55,780 --> 01:02:59,180
Previous trends were stopped by us


1637
01:02:59,180 --> 01:03:00,500
They were stopped


1638
01:03:00,500 --> 01:03:03,540
If they stopped, why are there more than 30 projects still violating regulations?


1639
01:03:03,540 --> 01:03:07,420
As the Xiaoyi municipal government, our attitude is clear and firm


1640
01:03:07,420 --> 01:03:08,900
If your attitude is clear and firm


1641
01:03:08,900 --> 01:03:10,260
Then these unlawful projects should be


1642
01:03:10,260 --> 01:03:11,820
Not one should have started


1643
01:03:13,440 --> 01:03:15,260
Liu Xiangdong - Bureau Chief, Shanxi Provincial Environmental Protection Bureau


1644
01:03:15,260 --> 01:03:18,860
This cat, it's the local government's cat


1645
01:03:18,860 --> 01:03:21,540
Whether this cat can catch mice or not


1646
01:03:21,540 --> 01:03:23,620
and how many mice it can catch, is decided by the local government


1647
01:03:23,620 --> 01:03:24,740
It is not decided by the environmental protection authority


1648
01:03:24,740 --> 01:03:29,620
We walked for hundreds of meters along the coastline and saw the same black chemical silt


1649
01:03:29,620 --> 01:03:31,980
We could smell 4-5 different kinds of chemicals


1650
01:03:31,980 --> 01:03:35,180
The odor here is the kind of smell that stings your nose


1651
01:03:35,180 --> 01:03:36,260
What is that smell?


1652
01:03:36,260 --> 01:03:37,570
Chen Zhiming - Vice General Manager, Zhejiang Haizheng Pharmaceutical


1653
01:03:37,570 --> 01:03:39,420
My sense of smell may not be as sensitive as yours


1654
01:03:40,220 --> 01:03:41,660
You said that you cannot smell it


1655
01:03:44,380 --> 01:03:49,580
My sensitivity is not as good as yours (laughter)


1656
01:03:52,580 --> 01:03:53,260
One ton of steel


1657
01:03:53,260 --> 01:03:56,260
if you cut all the costs of environmental protection measures


1658
01:03:56,260 --> 01:04:00,140
you could save 100 RMB ($16) per ton


1659
01:04:00,140 --> 01:04:03,580
For one ton of coal, you could save 156 RMB ($25)


1660
01:04:03,580 --> 01:04:08,620
On one truck, if you avoid installing any environmental protection equipment you can save 20,000 RMB ($3,200)


1661
01:04:08,620 --> 01:04:10,620
If you avoid upgrading petroleum products by a single grade


1662
01:04:10,620 --> 01:04:13,660
you can save 50 billion RMB ($8 billion)


1663
01:04:13,660 --> 01:04:14,820
10 years ago


1664
01:04:14,820 --> 01:04:16,940
I asked what the smell in the air was


1665
01:04:16,940 --> 01:04:19,380
I received no answer


1666
01:04:19,380 --> 01:04:21,620
Now I know


1667
01:04:21,620 --> 01:04:24,580
It is the stink of money


1668
01:04:24,580 --> 01:04:25,900
In that interview I recorded years ago


1669
01:04:25,900 --> 01:04:28,380
the local secretary said to me:


1670
01:04:28,380 --> 01:04:32,420
“You absolutely must film my achievements in pollution management!”


1671
01:04:32,420 --> 01:04:34,300
So he made me film this clip


1672
01:04:39,340 --> 01:04:42,740
He was quite satisfied and said


1673
01:04:42,740 --> 01:04:47,140
Miss Chai, I demolished this smokestack especially for you! (laughter)


1674
01:04:47,140 --> 01:04:48,980
3 years later, I went there again


1675
01:04:48,980 --> 01:04:52,100
An even larger smokestack had been built in the same place (laughter)


1676
01:04:52,100 --> 01:04:53,540
Actually, environmental protection facilities were installed at the same time


1677
01:04:53,540 --> 01:04:55,780
But when I asked: "Have the facilities ever been used?"


1678
01:04:55,780 --> 01:04:57,860
The manager rubbed his hands together, and answered, "Yes… Soon, soon."


1679
01:05:00,060 --> 01:05:01,620
At that time the local secretary said to me:


1680
01:05:01,620 --> 01:05:03,740
“Everyone tells me, 'Environmental Protection, Environmental Protection...'


1681
01:05:03,740 --> 01:05:07,500
Let me ask you, who would dare slow down China's economic development?"


1682
01:05:07,500 --> 01:05:09,060
I am also keen to know the answer


1683
01:05:09,060 --> 01:05:11,900
So 10 years later, I visited a steel market in Hebei Province


1684
01:05:13,380 --> 01:05:16,540
When I went in it was quite empty


1685
01:05:16,540 --> 01:05:18,700
The raw steel was already rusting


1686
01:05:18,700 --> 01:05:20,300
hidden in the wild grass


1687
01:05:20,300 --> 01:05:22,780
Some of it had even become birds' nests


1688
01:05:22,780 --> 01:05:25,380
I asked this young steel salesman:


1689
01:05:25,380 --> 01:05:26,900
“How is your business?”


1690
01:05:26,900 --> 01:05:29,660
He replied: “Do you see any trucks coming to carry the steel?”


1691
01:05:29,660 --> 01:05:30,900
He said, “So many steel enterprises


1692
01:05:30,900 --> 01:05:32,260
all produce completely identical,


1693
01:05:32,260 --> 01:05:34,460
low–end products


1694
01:05:34,460 --> 01:05:37,940
They compete with each other only on the basis of quantity


1695
01:05:37,940 --> 01:05:40,060
At this point I'd rather be selling cabbages!”


1696
01:05:41,700 --> 01:05:43,900
When we produce one ton of steel


1697
01:05:43,900 --> 01:05:45,700
how many resources will we consume?


1698
01:05:47,580 --> 01:05:49,020
600 kilograms of coal


1699
01:05:49,020 --> 01:05:50,380
3 to 6 tons of water


1700
01:05:50,380 --> 01:05:51,700
And what pollutants will we emit?


1701
01:05:51,700 --> 01:05:53,060
1.53 kilograms of sulfur dioxide


1702
01:05:53,060 --> 01:05:54,780
1 kilogram of smoke and soot


1703
01:05:54,780 --> 01:05:58,740
And what is the profit for producing one ton of steel?


1704
01:05:58,740 --> 01:05:59,740
You can take a guess


1705
01:06:02,220 --> 01:06:03,060
How much?


1706
01:06:04,260 --> 01:06:05,300
RMB 1000 ($160)?


1707
01:06:06,580 --> 01:06:09,180
Not even enough to buy a pickled egg


1708
01:06:09,180 --> 01:06:12,660
One ton of stell, in 2014


1709
01:06:12,660 --> 01:06:14,220
was less than 2 RMB ($0.30)


1710
01:06:14,220 --> 01:06:16,100
What about when we burn one ton of coal?


1711
01:06:16,100 --> 01:06:18,340
How much pollution will we release?


1712
01:06:18,340 --> 01:06:19,580
1.53 kilograms of sulfur dioxide


1713
01:06:19,580 --> 01:06:21,020
3 to 9 kilograms of nitrogen dioxide


1714
01:06:21,020 --> 01:06:22,380
2 kilograms of carbon monoxide


1715
01:06:22,380 --> 01:06:23,540
9-11 kilograms of soot


1716
01:06:23,540 --> 01:06:27,700
Can you guess how much profit there is in one ton of coal?


1717
01:06:27,700 --> 01:06:29,980
Two pickled eggs?


1718
01:06:29,980 --> 01:06:31,980
You're still overestimating


1719
01:06:31,980 --> 01:06:35,300
You couldn't even afford a soda


1720
01:06:35,300 --> 01:06:37,780
Of our 36 different heavy industries


1721
01:06:37,780 --> 01:06:40,460
22 are in serious overproduction


1722
01:06:40,460 --> 01:06:41,860
Mr Cao Xianghong from Sinopec


1723
01:06:41,860 --> 01:06:43,580
said one thing that was very accurate:


1724
01:06:43,580 --> 01:06:45,620
“It's like a person who looks big


1725
01:06:45,620 --> 01:06:48,140
but it's all fat and no muscle.”


1726
01:06:48,140 --> 01:06:53,940
But these enterprises are still receiving  large subsidies


1727
01:06:53,940 --> 01:06:57,660
You can see here, between 2011 – 2013


1728
01:06:57,660 --> 01:07:00,580
the government has given these publicly traded steel companies


1729
01:07:00,580 --> 01:07:02,100
this many subsidies


1730
01:07:02,100 --> 01:07:03,580
In order to prevent one of the companies


1731
01:07:03,580 --> 01:07:04,940
from being taken off the stock exchange


1732
01:07:04,940 --> 01:07:06,780
the government subsidized it every other year


1733
01:07:06,780 --> 01:07:07,980
How much has it been subsidized?


1734
01:07:07,980 --> 01:07:11,940
Tens, thousands, ten thousands, billions...


1735
01:07:13,300 --> 01:07:16,220
2 billion RMB ($320 million)


1736
01:07:16,220 --> 01:07:19,180
Two years later, another 2 billion RMB


1737
01:07:19,180 --> 01:07:22,140
Another one of these companies which had already posted severe losses


1738
01:07:22,140 --> 01:07:26,740
hung a slogan in their office after receiving the subsidy


1739
01:07:26,740 --> 01:07:29,820
It reads: “With intense struggle and indomitable spirit,


1740
01:07:29,820 --> 01:07:33,020
we vow that our steel will be 100 RMB ($16) cheaper than XX Corporation's.”


1741
01:07:33,020 --> 01:07:37,340
That's why the Deputy Head of the Central Bank, Mr Liu Shiyu, has called these companies ‘zombie companies’


1742
01:07:37,340 --> 01:07:39,540
They are consuming huge amounts of financial resources


1743
01:07:39,540 --> 01:07:42,780
They are going to bring a huge amount of unforeseeable risk to our real economy


1744
01:07:42,780 --> 01:07:45,220
And these companies are still expanding, even now


1745
01:07:45,220 --> 01:07:47,900
Two days ago I received a letter from a little girl


1746
01:07:47,900 --> 01:07:50,660
She said to me, a coke plant near her home


1747
01:07:50,660 --> 01:07:53,540
is expanding and is going to demolish her family's house


1748
01:07:53,540 --> 01:07:56,020
Her dad refused to agree, and so he was beaten


1749
01:07:56,020 --> 01:07:57,500
She hoped I could help her


1750
01:07:59,140 --> 01:08:01,620
This is the same little girl I interviewed ten years ago


1751
01:08:01,620 --> 01:08:04,220
Little Wang Huiqing, who had never seen stars or white clouds


1752
01:08:04,220 --> 01:08:05,740
I asked her, “How is your health these days?”


1753
01:08:05,740 --> 01:08:07,260
She told me, “Auntie, I can't worry about my health now.


1754
01:08:07,260 --> 01:08:09,580
I just want my whole family to have a place to live.”


1755
01:08:11,140 --> 01:08:13,740
Thank goodness, when I gave her a call two days ago she said


1756
01:08:13,740 --> 01:08:16,140
the owner of the coke plant had just been taken away by the authorities (laughter)


1757
01:08:17,980 --> 01:08:21,220
But, as for these industries that are already considered to be excessively over-producing


1758
01:08:21,220 --> 01:08:23,860
in half of the provinces of China, they are still listed as ‘key industries’


1759
01:08:23,860 --> 01:08:26,380
in the 25th Five-Year Plan for economic development.


1760
01:08:26,380 --> 01:08:28,380
There is a simple underlying reason


1761
01:08:28,380 --> 01:08:32,220
If we urbanize and continue to develop we only need to increase urbanization by 1%


1762
01:08:32,220 --> 01:08:33,580
and all this excess supply could easily be consumed


1763
01:08:33,580 --> 01:08:35,340
Where there is housing development, there is demand for steel


1764
01:08:35,340 --> 01:08:36,980
Where there is road construction there will be cars


1765
01:08:36,980 --> 01:08:37,500
Right?


1766
01:08:38,820 --> 01:08:40,780
Mr Jiang from Tsinghua University told me


1767
01:08:40,780 --> 01:08:44,340
China's urban development is itself in a severe state of over-production


1768
01:08:44,340 --> 01:08:46,820
The situation is even worse than in industry


1769
01:08:46,820 --> 01:08:48,140
I didn't really believe it


1770
01:08:48,140 --> 01:08:49,660
because I feel like over the past 30 years


1771
01:08:49,660 --> 01:08:51,940
social changes in ordinary families such as mine


1772
01:08:51,940 --> 01:08:53,220
and improvement in general living standards


1773
01:08:53,220 --> 01:08:55,020
were all achieved thanks to urbanization


1774
01:08:55,940 --> 01:09:00,060
When I was young my little sister and I grew up in a traditional house


1775
01:09:00,060 --> 01:09:01,580
It had 300 years of history


1776
01:09:01,580 --> 01:09:03,100
It housed a dozen families


1777
01:09:03,100 --> 01:09:06,780
Later, our living conditions improved when we moved into housing provided by my mom’s work unit


1778
01:09:06,780 --> 01:09:10,860
The accommodation we were given was 12 square meters and housed five of us


1779
01:09:10,860 --> 01:09:14,300
When we slept at night we added another wooden plank


1780
01:09:14,300 --> 01:09:16,540
to the bed frame and put a chair underneath to hold it up


1781
01:09:16,540 --> 01:09:17,860
Then it became a double bed


1782
01:09:19,140 --> 01:09:20,940
This was the window of my bedroom


1783
01:09:20,940 --> 01:09:23,100
Wasn’t it nice?


1784
01:09:23,100 --> 01:09:25,380
In reality the bedroom was very small, there was no window


1785
01:09:25,380 --> 01:09:27,460
so I could only hang a picture on the wall


1786
01:09:27,460 --> 01:09:30,500
It represented the fantasies of a very young creative spirit


1787
01:09:32,460 --> 01:09:35,020
This picture was taken when I was about to go off to university


1788
01:09:35,020 --> 01:09:36,500
It shows what our county seat looked like


1789
01:09:36,500 --> 01:09:39,060
I used to walk to school along this road


1790
01:09:39,060 --> 01:09:41,340
This is what it was like back in those days


1791
01:09:41,340 --> 01:09:43,140
The changes in living standards my family saw over the years


1792
01:09:43,140 --> 01:09:45,980
proves that there are millions of households all in need of new construction


1793
01:09:45,980 --> 01:09:46,860
(Mr Jiang) asked me


1794
01:09:46,860 --> 01:09:48,820
“Hasn't it been a long time since you last went back to Shanxi?”


1795
01:09:48,820 --> 01:09:49,660
I said he was right


1796
01:09:49,660 --> 01:09:51,460
He said, “Why don’t you go back and have a look?”


1797
01:09:51,460 --> 01:09:53,860
This year I took my child to visit Shanxi


1798
01:09:53,860 --> 01:09:56,540
and took this video with my phone along the way


1799
01:10:08,790 --> 01:10:13,960
(Billboards advertising new apartment complexes)


1800
01:10:49,860 --> 01:10:52,700
I am happy to see some changes happening in my hometown


1801
01:10:52,700 --> 01:10:55,340
because people there need wealth, they need development


1802
01:10:55,340 --> 01:10:56,780
But what surprises me


1803
01:10:56,780 --> 01:10:59,220
is that I saw so many advertisements for real estate


1804
01:10:59,260 --> 01:11:00,940
within the city, and so many construction sites


1805
01:11:00,940 --> 01:11:02,380
But they're empty


1806
01:11:02,420 --> 01:11:04,820
I then asked a relative who has invested a lot in the local housing market


1807
01:11:04,820 --> 01:11:07,100
how many flats in this particular development have been sold


1808
01:11:07,100 --> 01:11:08,660
He said, only 20-30% have been sold


1809
01:11:08,660 --> 01:11:10,140
I asked, “How come they've sold so few?”


1810
01:11:10,140 --> 01:11:11,660
He hesitated and said:


1811
01:11:11,660 --> 01:11:13,020
“Since the real name policy was implemented


1812
01:11:13,020 --> 01:11:15,500
for government officials buying real estate, they haven’t been selling too well.”


1813
01:11:15,500 --> 01:11:19,460
(My relative) booked a local hotel for my family


1814
01:11:19,460 --> 01:11:21,180
I was so shocked when I arrived at the hotel gate


1815
01:11:21,180 --> 01:11:25,140
because it claims to be a “five-star hotel”


1816
01:11:25,140 --> 01:11:27,380
and I was booked into the “Presidential Suite”


1817
01:11:27,380 --> 01:11:28,460
I said, “No you don’t have to!”


1818
01:11:28,460 --> 01:11:29,540
He said, “Don’t worry


1819
01:11:29,540 --> 01:11:33,300
It only costs 200 RMB ($32 USD).” (laughter)


1820
01:11:33,300 --> 01:11:36,660
We drove our car into the parking lot


1821
01:11:36,660 --> 01:11:39,940
and it didn't have a single light, it was in total darkness


1822
01:11:39,940 --> 01:11:42,980
And then this middle-aged guy came along carrying a big flashlight


1823
01:11:42,980 --> 01:11:44,100
to light our way


1824
01:11:44,100 --> 01:11:46,420
He guided us into the hotel lobby


1825
01:11:46,420 --> 01:11:49,700
He then continued to use his big flashlight and led us down the corridors to our room


1826
01:11:49,700 --> 01:11:53,580
There were no lights in the entire hotel because nobody was staying in it


1827
01:11:55,460 --> 01:11:56,300
When I got back to Beijing


1828
01:11:56,300 --> 01:11:57,980
I brought this up with Professor Jiang


1829
01:11:57,980 --> 01:12:01,940
He told me, "The Shanxi that you witnessed is a microcosm of the rest of the country


1830
01:12:01,940 --> 01:12:05,100
In China we lose 80 traditional villages everyday


1831
01:12:05,100 --> 01:12:07,940
Houses have an average lifespan of a mere 30 years


1832
01:12:07,940 --> 01:12:09,820
There are more than 200 municipalities in China


1833
01:12:09,820 --> 01:12:14,220
184 of which have plans to become so-called “international metropolises”


1834
01:12:14,220 --> 01:12:15,580
We have a population of 1.3 billion


1835
01:12:15,580 --> 01:12:18,540
If we take into account the plans laid out by these municipalities


1836
01:12:18,540 --> 01:12:20,460
the population adds up to 3.4 billion


1837
01:12:21,340 --> 01:12:24,500
I came to Beijing carrying a small suitcase in 1998


1838
01:12:24,500 --> 01:12:28,700
I studied, worked and found, in this city


1839
01:12:28,700 --> 01:12:30,500
a sense of self-worth and belonging


1840
01:12:30,500 --> 01:12:33,460
If China hadn’t been urbanized, I’d still be back in Shanxi


1841
01:12:33,460 --> 01:12:35,660
Working a menial job that my parents found for me


1842
01:12:35,660 --> 01:12:38,300
Wearing blue overalls and spending the rest of my life using an abacus


1843
01:12:38,300 --> 01:12:45,220
Cities gave us our personal freedom and gave this nation three decades of prosperity


1844
01:12:45,220 --> 01:12:47,580
When there are 300-400 million people knocking on our cities’ doors


1845
01:12:47,580 --> 01:12:49,980
Urbanization becomes an unavoidable reality


1846
01:12:49,980 --> 01:12:53,380
and those who enter will bring unimaginable culture and wealth to this country


1847
01:12:53,380 --> 01:12:55,820
But if we don't change our current model of using capital


1848
01:12:55,820 --> 01:12:59,900
to fuel industry and urban development, what will be the consequences?


1849
01:12:59,900 --> 01:13:02,660
The Development Research Center of the State Council projects that in 15 years


1850
01:13:02,700 --> 01:13:04,860
our coal consumption will rise to 6 billion tons


1851
01:13:04,860 --> 01:13:07,300
while the number of vehicles will rise to 400 million


1852
01:13:07,300 --> 01:13:08,300
So what does that mean for us?


1853
01:13:08,340 --> 01:13:09,940
Professor Ni of Tsinghua University told me


1854
01:13:09,940 --> 01:13:12,820
“This means that even before we run out of natural resources,


1855
01:13:12,820 --> 01:13:14,820
we will have exhausted the capacity of our environment.”


1856
01:13:14,820 --> 01:13:15,940
This means that now in China


1857
01:13:15,980 --> 01:13:20,700
the pollution and traffic jams have just started


1858
01:13:24,530 --> 01:13:25,680
The needs of a country


1859
01:13:25,680 --> 01:13:27,680
Beijing


1860
01:13:29,770 --> 01:13:32,560
Nanjing, Xi'an, Chengdu


1861
01:14:32,500 --> 01:14:34,620
This photo was taken during the November 2014 APEC summit in Beijing


1862
01:14:34,620 --> 01:14:39,500
One morning, my husband took me to a place he often visited as a child


1863
01:14:39,500 --> 01:14:44,340
His father taught him ice skating, swimming, and fishing there


1864
01:14:45,780 --> 01:14:49,620
He said he loved to look at the texture of the ice in winter


1865
01:14:49,620 --> 01:14:52,740
It spread all the way to the corner turret of the Forbidden City


1866
01:14:52,740 --> 01:14:57,820
That was his memory of this elegant and ancient city


1867
01:14:57,820 --> 01:15:02,220
We looked at this scene together like a kid staring at the last piece of candy


1868
01:15:02,220 --> 01:15:04,420
You know that if you don't eat it, it will melt


1869
01:15:04,420 --> 01:15:06,380
But you also know that once you eat it, it will disappear


1870
01:15:06,380 --> 01:15:09,660
Now we felt that same sense of sweetness, anxiety and frustration


1871
01:15:09,660 --> 01:15:10,740
Wang Yuesi, Researcher, Chinese Academy of Sciences, Institute of Atmospheric Physics


1872
01:15:10,740 --> 01:15:12,660
I am a native of Beijing


1873
01:15:12,660 --> 01:15:14,500
When I was a child, the sky was blue and the clouds were white


1874
01:15:14,500 --> 01:15:17,020
The canal water was so clear we could see the bottom, we could catch fish with our hands


1875
01:15:17,020 --> 01:15:18,940
I also grew up here


1876
01:15:18,940 --> 01:15:20,980
I also remember what it was like when I was still a child


1877
01:15:20,980 --> 01:15:23,380
Standing on Chang'an Avenue, we could see all the way to the Western Hills


1878
01:15:23,380 --> 01:15:25,980
Having clean air is not an impossible task


1879
01:15:25,980 --> 01:15:27,620
It's completely achievable


1880
01:15:27,620 --> 01:15:29,780
It just depends how determined you are


1881
01:15:29,780 --> 01:15:35,340
I hope and believe that with dedication and hard work, we'll be able to keep our "APEC Blue"


1882
01:15:37,180 --> 01:15:39,260
When I got back, I asked the experts at the Chinese Academy of Sciences:


1883
01:15:39,260 --> 01:15:43,380
“Can you tell me, what would it take if we want to keep our APEC Blue?”


1884
01:15:44,220 --> 01:15:48,380
He said, we must cut emissions of sulfur dioxide by this much against 2013 levels


1885
01:15:48,380 --> 01:15:49,780
nitrogen oxide by this much


1886
01:15:49,780 --> 01:15:51,260
and PM2.5 by this much


1887
01:15:51,260 --> 01:15:56,020
In short, we would have to cut our pollutants by more than half in exchange for that blue sky


1888
01:15:57,230 --> 01:15:59,700
During the APEC Summit, China and the US issued a joint statement


1889
01:15:59,920 --> 01:16:02,370
China pledged that its carbon emissions will peak around 2030


1890
01:16:02,370 --> 01:16:05,050
and non-fossil energy sources will make up 20% of its energy infrastructure


1891
01:16:05,050 --> 01:16:06,540
Coal dominates our country's energy infrastructure


1892
01:16:06,540 --> 01:16:08,260
and is a source of both carbon emissions and smog


1893
01:16:08,260 --> 01:16:10,220
Reducing our carbon output and cutting toxic emissions go hand in hand


1894
01:16:10,220 --> 01:16:13,900
When I set the goal for 2030, I specified that should be our peak


1895
01:16:13,900 --> 01:16:16,100
It is actually a “reverse coercion system.”


1896
01:16:16,100 --> 01:16:18,500
So we will start moving on the green, low-carbon path


1897
01:16:18,500 --> 01:16:22,500
People may ask, to protect the environment, do we really have to sacrifice economic development?


1898
01:16:22,500 --> 01:16:23,780
That's a debt you have to settle


1899
01:16:23,780 --> 01:16:26,540
If you've acted wrongly before, you have to make up for it now


1900
01:16:26,540 --> 01:16:30,060
The real problem now becomes, how do we increase the employment rate and the average income?


1901
01:16:30,060 --> 01:16:30,980
Through transformation


1902
01:16:30,980 --> 01:16:35,100
What if during this transformation some workers in some industries lose their jobs?


1903
01:16:35,180 --> 01:16:40,540
Right now, China's energy-saving and environmental protection industries generate over 3.7 trillion RMB ($590 billion) a year


1904
01:16:40,540 --> 01:16:44,100
and employ around 39 million people


1905
